# PR-Triage Skill

## Purpose

Classify a Testray build's failing tests as caused / not-caused by a
specific PR's changes in liferay-portal.

Sister to `apps/triage` (build-triage). Where build-triage compares
two builds and surfaces PASSED→FAILED transitions, PR-triage compares
*one* build against the project's full failure history. There is no
clean baseline build — the project's history *is* the baseline.

A failure is **unique** if no prior build in the project has produced
the same `(case_id, normalized_error)` signature. Only unique failures
go to classification — recurring/upstream failures are filtered in
code, not by the classifier.

## Workflow shape

Single mode in v0.3: bundle → Claude Code session classifies → write
`results.json`. API mode (planned v0.4) consumes the same bundle.
DB write to `fact_pr_triage_results` (planned v0.5) is staging-grade
— eventual destination is the Testray platform itself, so don't
over-invest in that schema.

```
run.sh
  ├── Testray API: /o/c/builds/{id}, /o/testray-rest/v1.0/...
  ├── working_db:  resolve case_ids, fetch FAILED history per case
  ├── normalize.py: regex chain + md5 → error signature hashes
  ├── classify:    UNIQUE_NEW_TEST / UNIQUE_NEW_ERROR / NOT_UNIQUE
  ├── pr_diff.py:  git diff merge-base(base,target)..target
  ├── hunk_match:  per unique row, token-substring match against diff paths
  └── bundle.py:   write runs/r_<id>/
                     ↓
            Claude Code session classifies
                     ↓
                results.json
                     ↓
       v0.4 API mode (planned) / v0.5 submit (planned)
```

## CLI contract

```bash
bash apps/pr-triage/run.sh \
  --target-branch  PR-38301 \
  --target-source  api \
  --target-build-id 471865557 \
  --base-branch    release-2026.q1
```

All four args are required. `--target-source api` is the only mode
in v0.3; `tar` and `db` are planned. `--base-branch` is required
specifically because a wrong base silently produces a garbage diff;
the script verifies merge-base resolves before doing any work.

## Bundle file contracts

`apps/pr-triage/runs/r_<ts>_<branch>_<build>/`:

| File | Shape / purpose |
|---|---|
| `run.yml`             | YAML metadata: `run_id`, `target_branch`, `base_branch`, `target_build_id`, `build.{project_id, routine_id, duedate, name}`, `diff.{merge_base, files_changed, lines_changed}`, `unique_counts.{unique_new_test, unique_new_error, not_unique}`, `prepared_at`, `classifier: agent:claude-opus-4-7`. |
| `unique_rows.csv`      | Columns: `case_id, verdict, case_name, component, team, flaky, error_hash, prior_failure_count, prior_distinct_hashes, matched_files_count, error`. One row per unique failure. |
| `hunks.txt`           | Per-unique-row matched diff hunks, separated by row markers. Empty hunk block means tokens didn't match anything in the diff — fall back to `diff_full.diff`. |
| `diff_full.diff`      | Unfiltered output of `git diff $(merge-base BASE TARGET) TARGET`. The source of truth — `hunks.txt` is a derived view. |
| `prompt.md`           | Inline per-row data + rubric. Generated from the same data as `unique_rows.csv` for in-session reading. |
| `results.schema.json` | JSON Schema. Validates `results.json`. |
| `results.json`        | **Written by the classifier.** One object per unique row. |

## Verdicts (results.json)

`PR_CAUSED` / `NEEDS_REVIEW` / `FALSE_POSITIVE`. Different from
build-triage's `BUG / NEEDS_REVIEW / FALSE_POSITIVE` — PR-triage's
question is PR-attribution specifically, so `PR_CAUSED` replaces
`BUG`. `FALSE_POSITIVE` keeps the same meaning (failure unrelated
to the PR).

`culprit_file` and `specific_change` are **required** for
`PR_CAUSED`. The schema rejects rows that omit them.

## Uniqueness model — why it works without a baseline build

| Uniqueness verdict | Meaning | Action |
|---|---|---|
| `UNIQUE_NEW_TEST`  | `case_id` has zero prior occurrences in this project's history. | Classify (likely PR added a new test). |
| `UNIQUE_NEW_ERROR` | `case_id` has prior failures, but this exact normalized-error hash is new. | Classify (signature suggests unique cause). |
| `NOT_UNIQUE`       | This `(case_id, normalized_error)` has been seen before in the project. | Not classified — filtered in code. |

Filter scope: same project (auto-resolved from build metadata), any
routine, status = FAILED only, builds with `duedate < target.duedate`.

Normalization rules in `normalize.py`: strip ISO timestamps, hex
addresses (`0x…`, `@…`), `Thread-N`, `pid=N`, stack-frame line
numbers (`:N)` → `:)`), collapse whitespace. Then md5. Hash collision
risk is negligible at the scale of one project's failure history.

## Differences vs build-triage

| Concern | build-triage | PR-triage |
|---|---|---|
| Comparison axis | Two builds (PASSED→FAILED transitions) | One build vs project history (unique failure signatures) |
| Baseline requirement | A clean passing baseline build | None — history is the baseline |
| Diff source | `dim_build.git_hash_a` → `_b` | `git diff merge-base(base, target)..target` |
| Module → component lookup | `dim_module_component_map` (RAP DB) | None — substring tokens only |
| Verdicts | BUG / NEEDS_REVIEW / FALSE_POSITIVE | PR_CAUSED / NEEDS_REVIEW / FALSE_POSITIVE |
| Output table | `fact_triage_results` | `fact_pr_triage_results` (planned v0.5, staging-grade) |

## Data dependencies

- **Testray API** (`config.yml: testray.{base_url, client_id, client_secret}`) — OAuth2 client_credentials.
- **`testray_working_db`** (`config.yml: databases.testray_working_db`) — raw Testray backup. Per `db/testray_analytical_README.md`, this DB is intended-droppable after the analytical bootstrap; PR-triage requires it restored.
- **liferay-portal checkout** (`config.yml: git.repo_path`) — both `--target-branch` and `--base-branch` must exist as local refs.

## Schema details — testray_working_db

Tables used:

- `o_22235989312226_caseresult`
  - `c_caseresultid_` (PK)
  - `r_buildtocaseresult_c_buildid` → build FK
  - `r_casetocaseresult_c_caseid` → case FK
  - `duestatus_` — status enum, `'FAILED'` for failed
  - `errors_` — full error text (TEXT, no truncation)
- `o_22235989312226_build`
  - `c_buildid_` (PK)
  - `r_projecttobuilds_c_projectid` — project filter
  - `duedate_` — chronological cut

Indexes that make the per-case history query fast:
`ix_a8d74b8d (caseresult.r_buildtocaseresult_c_buildid)`,
`ix_951b8237 (caseresult.r_casetocaseresult_c_caseid)`,
`ix_bcb6a688 (build.r_projecttobuilds_c_projectid)`.

## When to stop and ask the user

- The build's `duedate` predates the PR's earliest commit — no failure
  can be PR-caused; surface and confirm before classifying everything
  as FALSE_POSITIVE.
- `unique_new_test + unique_new_error == 0` — nothing to classify, surface
  the verdict and stop.
- `diff_full.diff` is empty or trivial (< 5 changed lines) but unique
  failures exist — likely wrong base branch.
- Many unique rows have `matched_files_count = 0` and the test names
  don't thematically connect to the diff — likely token matching is
  too narrow; flag rather than classify all as FALSE_POSITIVE.
- Two pieces of evidence contradict (matched hunks point to PR_CAUSED
  but the error is a known flake pattern with `flaky=True`).

## Backlog and known caveats

- **v0.4 API mode** — bundle shape stays the same; only the consumer
  changes. Build it on top of `apps/triage/classify_api.py` with
  prompt caching against the rubric header. Will reuse OAuth2,
  pagination, and Anthropic SDK patterns.
- **v0.5 submit** — `fact_pr_triage_results` columns deferred until
  we see real classification volume. Staging-grade table; eventual
  destination is the Testray platform itself.
- **Hunk match heuristic** — token substring matching on test name
  + component / team. Misses transitive deps; bundle includes
  `diff_full.diff` for the classifier to fall back on. Same gap as
  build-triage; same mitigation.
- **Empty errors** — caseresults with empty `errors_` hash to the
  same empty signature and may cluster as NOT_UNIQUE with each other.
  Surface only if it skews counts in practice.
- **Stale working_db snapshot** — caseresult_ids on the target build
  newer than the snapshot fall back to UNIQUE_NEW_TEST with a `note`
  in evidence. Surface; don't pretend it's verified uniqueness.
- **Shared utils to apps/_common/** — once both triage apps stabilize,
  extract: Testray OAuth2 + paginated fetch, `/o/c/builds/{id}` and
  `/o/c/cases/{id}` lookups, psycopg2 helpers, portal-repo diff
  helpers, prompt.md / results.schema.json conventions. Tracked in
  the project backlog.

## What NOT to do

- Don't reuse build-triage's `BUG` label here. The verdict set is
  intentionally different.
- Don't reach into RAP fact tables (`dim_module_component_map`,
  `dim_component`) for module/component resolution — PR-triage is
  conceptually a Testray-domain tool and shouldn't couple to the
  RAP pipeline DB.
- Don't classify rows with `verdict = NOT_UNIQUE` — they're not in
  the bundle; if you see one, the bundle is malformed.
- Don't bypass the merge-base check — `git diff base..target` (two
  dots) gives a different (often wrong) diff than
  `git diff $(merge-base base target)..target` (the symmetric-ish
  PR-style diff).
- Don't recalibrate the normalization rules silently. Add to the
  list in `normalize.py` and document the trigger case in the next
  session.
